To change a tip cartridge:
# Place the iron in the tool stand.
# Grip the cartridge (use heat-resistant gloves if the iron was recently in use).
# Pull the cartridge straight out of the handle.
# Insert the new cartridge until it seats fully. The station automatically recognizes it.

== Temperature Presets (PS1 / PS2) ==
The ADS200 has two programmable temperature presets:

* '''PS1 (Setback / Idle):''' Program to 177C (350F). This is a low-temperature idle state that protects the tip from oxidation when the iron is in the stand.
* '''PS2 (Operating):''' Program to your working temperature (e.g., 345C / 650F for lead-free, 315C / 600F for leaded).

=== Programming Presets ===
# Press the '''Program''' key on the station front panel.
# Use the '''arrow keys''' to set the PS1 temperature (recommended: 177C / 350F).
# Press '''Program''' again to move to PS2.
# Use the arrow keys to set the PS2 operating temperature.
# Press '''Program''' again to confirm and exit programming mode.

=== Manual Setback ===
When stepping away from the station:
# Press the '''Program''' key once to drop the iron to the PS1 setback temperature. This extends tip life significantly.
# When ready to resume, press the '''Program''' key twice to return to the PS2 operating temperature. Recovery is rapid due to the 120W heater.

== Procedure ==

=== Startup ===
# Ensure the correct tip cartridge is installed for your work.
# Power on the station using the rear power switch.
# The display shows the current temperature, which ramps to the PS2 preset.
# The iron is ready within seconds — the AccuDrive system heats the cartridge extremely quickly.
# Tin the tip before beginning work.

=== During Use ===
# Solder using standard techniques (see Soldering Iron Safety SOP for joint technique).
# The AccuDrive system automatically senses thermal load and delivers power on demand — you should not need to increase temperature for brief high-demand joints (connectors, ground planes) as the system compensates dynamically.
# If you find the iron struggling with a large thermal mass, increase PS2 temperature by 10-20C rather than jumping to a much higher setting.
# Clean the tip frequently with the brass wool cleaner on the tool stand.

=== Idle Periods ===
# Return the iron to the tool stand.
# Press the '''Program''' key for manual setback to PS1 if stepping away for more than a few minutes.
# For the Instant SetBack (ISB) tool stand model: the station automatically drops to PS1 when the iron is placed in the stand and returns to PS2 when picked up.

=== Shutdown ===
# Tin the tip generously with fresh solder.
# Place the iron in the tool stand.
# Power off the station using the rear switch.

== Maintenance ==

=== After Each Session ===
* Tin the tip before shutdown.
* Clean the brass wool tip cleaner — tap out solder debris.
* Wipe down the iron handle and stand if flux has splattered on them.

=== Weekly ===
* Inspect the tip cartridge for wear. Replace if the plating is visibly damaged, the tip is pitted, or it no longer wets properly after applying tip tinner.
* Verify tip-to-ground resistance with a multimeter (should be less than 2 ohms). This is especially important for ESD-sensitive work.

=== Periodically ===
* Check the iron cord for heat damage or kinks near the handle connection.
* Verify temperature accuracy with a tip thermometer. The Blue Series cartridges should not drift, but the tip thermometer confirms the system is within spec.
* Clean the tool stand to remove accumulated solder and flux residue.

== Troubleshooting ==
* '''Iron not heating:''' Verify the station is powered on and the tip cartridge is fully seated. Try a different cartridge to rule out a cartridge failure.
* '''Temperature reading erratic:''' The tip cartridge sensor may be damaged. Replace the cartridge.
* '''Tip won't accept solder (black, oxidized):''' Apply Pace tip tinner/activator. If the tip doesn't recover, replace the cartridge. Ensure you are using the setback feature to prevent oxidation during idle.
* '''Weak thermal performance on large joints:''' Increase PS2 temperature by 10-20C. Use a larger chisel tip for better thermal transfer. Ensure the tip is clean and well-tinned.
* '''Display shows error:''' Power cycle the station. If the error persists, consult the Pace ADS200 operation manual.
